@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Installation
@remark ***********************************************************
@node Install "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                        ________________________
                         @{b}Grapevine Installation@{ub}
                        ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      Installation of Grapevine varies depending upon the method of
  communication used.

  @{b}@{u}AS225@{ub}@{uu}
  Presumably you have already extracted the Grapevine archive.  The directory
  structure is already set up properly in the archive.  In order for DCC to
  work correctly you may have to edit the @{"path settings" link PathConfig} so that Grapevine
  can find the DCC program files.

  @{b}@{u}AmiTCP@{ub}@{uu}
  When using AmiTCP, install Grapevine just like for AS225.  To use the
  program though you will need the AmiTCP socket.library by Henning
  Schmiedehausen.  This socket.library is included in the Grapevine archive
  and is also available on the Grapevine support site.
  
  The socket.library requires you to set the @{b}ENV:SOCKETCONFIG@{ub} variable in
  order for it to work.  Please refer to the socket.library manual for
  directions on setting this variable.

  @{b}@{u}Serial@{ub}@{uu}
  Serial operation requires more installation work than TCP.  Install the
  Grapevine program on your Amiga wherever desired.  The DCC files are not
  used in serial mode unless you are using DNet.  HFTgv must be present in
  the same directory as Grapevine.
  
  Included with HFTgv is a small utility called irclink, which is a simple
  network data connection program that must be installed on your Unix host.
  It simply establishes a link to the IRC server through which Grapevine
  can communicate.  To install irclink, you need to compile it with a C
  compiler.  The irclink source is provided as a shell script that you
  execute in order to produce the correct version of irclink for your
  system.  The default compiler used is "cc".  If you have trouble with that,
  try changing the "ccomp=cc" line at the top of irclink.sh to "ccomp=gcc" or
  some other compiler.  To compile irclink, type
  
                             sh irclink.sh

  For instructions on the use of HFTgv and irclink to connect to the
  server, see the @{"Serial" link Serial} section of the manual.
  
@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Serial operation
@remark ***********************************************************
@node Serial "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                      ____________________________
                       @{b}Grapevine Serial Operation@{ub}
                      ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      Grapevine supports any properly written serial.device.  It has been
  tested with serial.device, uw.device (Amiga UnixWindows by Ezra Story),
  and dnet.device.  However, note that dnet.device has a few problems.  See
  the @{"Bugs" link Bugs/Main} file for details.

  To connect to IRC in serial mode, follow these steps:
  
  1. Run HFTgv from the same directory in which Grapevine is installed.
  2. Login to your Unix account.
  3. Run the irclink program with your server name and optional port:
     "irclink servername [port]"
  4. Once connected to the server, select "Run Grapevine" from the HFTgv
     menu, or type RightAmiga-1.

  You should now be connected to IRC!
  
  For further instructions on using HFTgv, refer to @{"HFTgv.doc" link HFTgv.doc/Main}.

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Program Configuration
@remark ***********************************************************

@node Config "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                        _________________________
                         @{b}Grapevine Configuration@{ub}
                        ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      Grapevine has many features which can be customized to the user's
  preferences, as well as a number of items which are required to be set.
  There are three methods by which Grapevine is configured:  environment
  variables, the "Settings" menu items, and command line parameters.
      
  @{b}@{u}Environment Variables@{ub}@{uu}
  Grapevine recognizes three standard environment variables in TCP/IP
  setups:
  
           USER - System username (login name)
       REALNAME - Your full real name
       HOSTNAME - Your machine's host name

  These three variables are only read when no configuration file is found.
  Values saved in the settings files override the environment variables.

  If you are using socket.library for AmiTCP, you must set an additional
  variable named SOCKETCONFIG.  Refer to the socket.library manual for
  directions on the proper configuration.

  @{b}@{u}Settings Menu@{ub}@{uu}
  The @{"settings" link SettingsMenu} menu is available from any channel window, and contains many
  items which are used to configure the program.

  @{b}@{u}Command Line Parameters@{ub}@{uu}
  There are several command line parameters which may be specified.  These
  parameters all override values which are saved in the config files.  
  
        AS225 - Run Grapevine in TCP mode using AS225r2
       SERVER - IRC server name
         PORT - IRC server port
         PASS - IRC server password
     NICKNAME - Your nickname

  There are a number of command line parameters for serial operation which
  are not described here.  These parameters are NOT for your use! They are
  intended to be used exclusively by HFTgv.
  
@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Project Windows
@remark ***********************************************************

@node ProjectWindows "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@next Menus
                              _________________
                               @{b}Project Windows@{ub}
                              ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The operation of Grapevine centers around two windows: the channel
  window and the namelist window.
  
  @{b}@{u}Channel Window@{uu}@{ub}
  The channel window is where all of the IRC text is displayed, including
  messages, public channel conversation, command operation results, and
  errors.  You can have up to 10 channel windows open at a time, each of
  which has its own scrollback buffer.  The description of the channel window
  operation is broken up into the following sections:
  
      @{"Text display       " link TextDisplay} Area where communications are printed
      @{"String input gadget" link StringGadget} Gadget for input of messages and commands
      @{"Status indicator   " link StatusGadget} Indicates chanop/voice status
      @{"Window title       " link WindowTitle} Contains various useful information

  @{u}@{b}Namelist Window@{ub}@{uu}
  The namelist window contains a listview gadget displaying the names of the
  users on a joined channel.  The window opens immediately to the right of
  the channel window.  It can be closed safely, and reopened with either the
  @{"/NAMES" link NamesCmd} command or the @{"Names menu item" link NamesItem} in the channel menu.

  In the list of names, a small symbol may be located beside a nickname.
  A small magic wand indicates that the person is a channel operator, and a
  representation of sound waves indicates that the person has a "voice" on
  a moderated channel and can speak.

  You can perform various operations on users in the channel by selecting
  a nickname with the mouse and then clicking on one of the appropriate
  @{"icons" link Icons} or selecting an item from the @{"channel menu" link ChannelMenu}.  After an operation has
  been completed, the user will be deselected.  Double-clicking on a nickname
  will display @{"Who Is" link WhoIsItem} information on the user.

@endnode

@node TextDisplay "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                        ______________________________
                         @{b}Channel Window: Text Display@{ub}
                        ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The text display area is where all of the incoming and outgoing
  messages, error messages, and command results are displayed.  All of
  the text to the window is saved in a scrollback buffer, which can be
  viewed with the prop gadget in the window or with the following hotkeys:
  
               Ctrl CursorUp:  Jump to beginning of buffer
                Alt CursorUp:  Scroll up one page
              Alt CursorDown:  Scroll down one page
             Ctrl CursorDown:  Jump to end of buffer

  The size of the scrollback buffer is adjustable in the @{"Program Settings" link ProgramConfig}
  window, as well as is the number of pixels between messages.

  The text display area is actually a custom BOOPSI gadgetclass.  This has
  one caveat.  When the channel window is resized, all of the text in the
  scrollback buffer is word-wrapped.  This operation can take a couple of
  seconds on slower machines.  Since the wrapping is all done by the gadget,
  which is called by Intuition (input.device), all system input will freeze
  while the operation is done.  A wait pointer is displayed during this
  operation.

@endnode

@node StringGadget "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                        ______________________________
                         @{b}Channel Window: Input Gadget@{ub}
                        ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The string input gadget at the bottom of the channel window is where
  all commands and messages are entered.  This gadget is a much-enhanced
  GadTools string gadget.  The enhancements are all described below.

  @{b}@{u}Command Input@{ub}@{uu}
  Grapevine has over 50 @{"commands" link Commands} that can be entered in the input gadget.  To
  enter a command, precede it with a "/" character.  For example, to send a
  private message to a user with the nickname JillUser you would use the MSG
  command as follows:
  
            /MSG JillUser Hi there!  How are you doing tonight?

  Command interpretation is case-insensitive.
  
  If you do not enter a command on the input line, all text that you input
  will be sent to any channel you have joined in the current channel window.
  If you have not joined a channel, an error message will be displayed.

  @{u}@{b}Command History@{ub}@{uu}
  The string gadget has command history so that you can recall messages and
  commands that you have already typed.  To recall a line from the command
  history, use the up/down cursor keys to step through by single lines, and
  shift up/down to jump to the first/last entries in the history.  The last
  line is actually a clear input line.

  The maximum number of lines stored in the command history is adjustable in
  the @{"Program Settings" link ProgramConfig} window.

  @{b}@{u}Style and Bell Characters@{ub}@{uu}
  The string gadget will accept three control characters that will change the
  style of the message text.  These characters are as follows:
  
            Ctrl B:  Bold text
            Ctrl V:  Inverse text (light-on-dark)
            Ctrl _:  Underlined text

  To turn a style on, enter the appropriate character into the input gadget.
  To turn it off, enter the character again.  (Note: Depending on the font
  you are using, the characters may appear as garbage.)  You can mix styles.

  In addition to style characters, you can cause a bell to be heard on the
  other users' terminals by entering the "Ctrl G" bell character.  While you
  can send bell characters with Grapevine, received bells are not heard at
  this time.

  @{b}@{u}Horizontal Tabs@{ub}@{uu}
  Grapevine treats the tab key much like a word processor or text editor does.
  Horizontal tabs are set every four columns.  If you press the tab key in
  input character positions 1-3, the cursor will jump to position 4.
  Similarly, if you press tab in positions 4-7, the cursor will go to position
  8.  This feature allows you to dump source code into a channel window with
  all of the tabs properly lined up.

@endnode

@node StatusGadget "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                      __________________________________
                       @{b}Channel Window: Status Indicator@{ub}
                      ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The status indicator is located to the left of the string input gadget.
  There are two different images that are displayed in this gadget:
  
           Magic wand: Indicates you are a channel operator of the channel
                       you have joined in this window.
          Audio waves: Indicates you are allowed to speak in a moderated
                       channel (you have a "voice").

  The channel operator status takes precedence over voice status since a
  channel operator can also speak on a moderated channel.  If neither status
  applies to you, the indicator will be disabled (checkerboard pattern).

@endnode

@node WindowTitle "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                        ______________________________
                         @{b}Channel Window: Window Title@{ub}
                        ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The title bar of the channel windows displays several useful items.
  When a channel is joined in a window, the title format is as follows:

    [X mc] [-AWAY-] Channel #channel (modes) X users, X chanop: Topic.
     ^ ^^     ^                 ^       ^    ^        ^           ^
     A BC     D                 E       F    G        H           I

     A: Project number
     B: Lowercase 'm' means private messages are displayed in this window
     C: Lowercase 'c' means "crap" messages are displayed in this window
     D: If you are marked away, "-AWAY-" will appear in this position
     E: Name of the channel joined in this window
     F: Channel mode flags See @{"/MODE" link ModeCmd} for details.
     G: Number of users joined to this channel
     H: Number of channel operators in this channel
     I: Channel topic string.  Text is cropped if it will not fit.

  If no channel is joined in the window, items E-I do not appear in the
  title bar.

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Program Menus
@remark ***********************************************************

@node Menus "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@next Icons
                               _______________
                                @{b}Program Menus@{ub}
                               ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      Many of Grapevine's features are available through the program menus.
  Some things, such as program settings, are only available in the menus.
  Most others are accessible by other means, including icons and commands.

  @{b}@{u}Menus@{ub}@{uu}

  @{"Project " link ProjectMenu} Project, window, and program control
  @{"Channel " link ChannelMenu} Commands related to channel operation
  @{"Server  " link ServerMenu} Server and network control
  @{"Personal" link PersonalMenu} Operations related to your person
  @{"Misc    " link MiscMenu} Miscellaneous items that don't fit elsewhere
  @{"Settings" link SettingsMenu} Program configuration options

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Project Menu
@remark ***********************************************************
@node ProjectMenu "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                                ______________
                                 @{b}Project Menu@{ub}
                                ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The "Project" menu contains items related to manipulation of the
  channel windows.  Most of the items are standard entries found in most
  Amiga programs.

  @{u}@{b}Menu items@{ub}@{uu}

  @{"New Window        " link NewWindowItem} Open a new channel project window.

  @{"Clear Buffer      " link ClearBufferItem} Clear the active project scrollback buffer.

  @{"Set Message Window" link SetMsgWinItem} Send private messages to the active window.
  @{"Set Crap Window   " link SetCrapWinItem} Send misc. results and errors to the active window.

  @{"Reveal            " link RevealItem} Activate the Next/Previous project window or the icon window.
  @{"Close             " link CloseItem} Close the active project window.

  @{"About             " link AboutItem} Display information about the program.
  @{"Quit              " link QuitItem} Exit the program.

@endnode

@node NewWindowItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                       _______________________________
                        @{b}Project Menu Item: New Window@{ub}
                       ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The "New Window" Menu Item opens a new channel window project. There
  is a maximum of 10 channel windows allowed to be open at a time.  If you
  try to open a new window if 10 are already open, a requester will inform
  you of this fact.

  See Also: @{"/OPENWIN" link OpenWinCmd}

@endnode

@node ClearBufferItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                      _________________________________
                       @{b}Project Menu Item: Clear Buffer@{ub}
                      ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The Clear Buffer Menu Item clears all lines in the scrollback buffer
  of the active channel window.  There is no confirmation for this item.

  See Also: @{"/CLEAR" link ClearCmd}

@endnode

@node SetMsgWinItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                   _______________________________________
                    @{b}Project Menu Item: Set Message Window@{ub}
                   ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      Selecting this Menu Item forces private messages and notices to be
  displayed in the active project window.  The current message window is
  indicated by a lowercase "m" next to the project number in the channel
  window title bar.

@endnode

@node SetCrapWinItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                     ____________________________________
                      @{b}Project Menu Item: Set Crap Window@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      Selecting this Menu Item forces certain error messages and various
  command results such as CTCP replies to be displayed in the active project
  window.  The current crap window is indicated by a lowercase "c" next to the
  project number in the channel window title bar.

@endnode

@node RevealItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                         ___________________________
                          @{b}Project Menu Item: Reveal@{ub}
                         ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      There are three items in the "Reveal" submenu.  Two of the items deal
  with channel project windows: "Next Channel", which activates the next
  channel window, and "Previous Channel", which activates the previous
  channel window.  The other item, "Icon Window", opens the icon window or
  brings it to the front if it is already open.  The open status of the icon
  window is saved in the settings file.

@endnode

@node CloseItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                          __________________________
                           @{b}Project Menu Item: Close@{ub}
                          ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      This menu item closes the current project window and all related
  windows.  If you have the @{"Confirm Requesters" link ConfReqs} "Settings" menu item enabled,
  a requester will ask you if you want to close or leave a channel if one is
  joined.

  See Also: @{"/CLOSEWIN" link CloseWinCmd}

@endnode

@node AboutItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                          __________________________
                           @{b}Project Menu Item: About @{ub}
                          ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The "About" menu item opens a window containing information about
  the program, including author, copyright, and support info.

  See Also: @{"/ABOUT" link AboutCmd}

@endnode

@node QuitItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                          _________________________
                           @{b}Project Menu Item: Quit@{ub}
                          ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The "Quit" item will terminate the program.  If you have enabled the
  @{"Confirm Requesters" link ConfReqs} "Settings" Menu Item, you will be asked to confirm
  the operation before the program exits.  The IRC signoff message will
  be the string you have set in the @{"User" link UserConfig} settings window.

  See Also: @{"/QUIT" link QuitCmd}

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Channel Menu
@remark ***********************************************************
@node ChannelMenu "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                               _______________
                                @{b} Channel Menu@{ub}
                               ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The "Channel" menu contains items that deal with examination and
  manipulation of channels and users on channels.

  @{u}@{b}Menu items@{ub}@{uu}

  @{"Join         " link JoinItem} Join a channel
  @{"Leave        " link LeaveItem} Leave a joined channel

  @{"Names        " link NamesItem} List names on the current channel
  @{"Who          " link WhoItem} More detailed list of users on channel

  @{"Who Is User  " link WhoIsItem} Display personal information on selected user
  @{"fileQuery User   " link QueryItem} Initiate query with a selected user
  @{"Ping User    " link PingItem} Send a ping message to selected user
  @{"Kick User    " link KickItem} Kick selected user off channel
  @{"Ban User     " link BanItem} Ban selected user from the channel
  @{"List Bans    " link BanListItem} List current bans on the channel

  @{"Channel Modes" link CModeItem} View/set channel modes

@endnode

@node JoinItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                          _________________________
                           @{b}Channel Menu Item: Join@{ub}
                          ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      "Join" opens a requester with a string gadget in which you can enter
  the name of the channel(s) you want to join.  The parameters are the same
  as those for the /JOIN command.  Note that you cannot join more than 10
  channels at once.

  See Also: @{"/JOIN" link JoinCmd}
            @{"Join Icon" link JoinIcon}

@endnode

@node LeaveItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                          __________________________
                           @{b}Channel Menu Item: Leave@{ub}
                          ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      "Leave" causes you to leave the channel joined in the current project
  window, if any.  If the @{"Confirm Requesters" link ConfReqs} option in the "Settings"
  menu is enabled, you will be asked to confirm the operation.

  See Also: @{"/LEAVE" link LeaveCmd}
            @{"Leave Icon" link LeaveIcon}

@endnode

@node NamesItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                          __________________________
                           @{b}Channel Menu Item: Names@{ub}
                          ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      This item displays a list of the nicknames of people joined to the
  current channel.  The names in the NameList window will be updated, and
  if the window was closed it will be reopened.

  Sample output:

    @{b}«Names»@{ub}  Users on #foobar: JoeUser, JaneUser, JillUser
    @{b}«Names»@{ub}  End of /NAMES list.

  See Also: @{"/NAMES" link NamesCmd}

@endnode

@node WhoItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                           ________________________
                            @{b}Channel Menu Item: Who@{ub}
                           ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The "Who" item displays a list of users on the current channel.
  Information displayed is as follows: channel, nickname, status, and
  user@host.  The status field contains four different symbols: H=here,
  G=gone (marked away), @=channel operator, and *=irc operator.

  Sample output:

    @{b}«Who»@{ub}  #blade       JoeUser  G@ juser@iastate.edu 
    @{b}«Who»@{ub}  #blade      JillUser  H@ jillu@os.freak.com
    @{b}«Who»@{ub}  End of Who info.

  See Also: @{"/WHO" link WhoCmd}

@endnode

@node WhoIsItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                       ________________________________
                        @{b}Channel Menu Item: Who Is User@{ub}
                       ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      This item displays personal information about the selected user in
  the channel names list.  You can also double-click on a user in the
  listview to get whois info.

  Sample output:

    @{b}«Who Is»@{ub}      User: JaneUser (janeu@os.freak.com): Jane A. User
    @{b}«Who Is»@{ub}  Channels: @#indigo
    @{b}«Who Is»@{ub}    Server: irc.iastate.edu - Iowa State Alternate Reality Server
    @{b}«Who Is»@{ub}      Idle: 132 seconds.
    @{b}«Who Is»@{ub}  End of WhoIs info.

  See Also: @{"/WHOIS" link WhoIsCmd}
            @{"Who Is Icon" link WhoIsIcon}

@endnode

@node QueryItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                        _______________________________
                         @{b}Channel Menu Item: Query User@{ub}
                        ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      If a user is selected in a channel userlist, this menu item will start
  a query with the user.  If query is already on and no user is selected,
  then query mode will be turned off.

  See Also: @{"/QUERY" link QueryCmd}
@endnode

@node PingItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                        ______________________________
                         @{b}Channel Menu Item: Ping User@{ub}
                        ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      This item causes a ping message to be sent to the user selected in the
  names listview.  The user's client simply bounces this message back.  The
  message contains a timestamp that is used to determine how much time
  elapsed between sending the message and receiving the echo.  Pinging
  gives an indication of current network performance.

  Sample Output:

    @{b}«Ping»@{ub}  Sending ping to JillUser.                   
    @{b}«Pong»@{ub}  Ping response time from JillUser: 9 seconds.

  See Also: @{"/PING" link PingCmd}
            @{"Ping Icon" link PingIcon}

@endnode

@node KickItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                        ______________________________
                         @{b}Channel Menu Item: Kick User@{ub}
                        ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      This item kicks the user currently selected in the channel names
  listview.  The screen will be beeped if no user is selected or if you
  are not a channel operator.  If the @{"Ask Kick Reason" link AskKickItem} option in the
  "Settings" menu is enabled, a requester is brought up containing the
  default kick message, with option to change it or cancel.

  See Also: @{"/KICK" link KickCmd}
            @{"Kick Icon" link KickIcon}

@endnode

@node BanItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                        _____________________________
                         @{b}Channel Menu Item: Ban User@{ub}
                        ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      This item will ban the selected user in the namelist from the current
  channel.  A string requester will come up with a default ban pattern for
  you to edit.  The screen will be beeped if no user is selected or if you
  are not a channel operator.

  See Also: @{"/BAN" link BanCmd}
            @{"Ban Icon" link BanIcon}

@endnode

@node BanListItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                        ______________________________
                         @{b}Channel Menu Item: List Bans@{ub}
                        ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      "List Bans" will display a list of bans currently imposed in the
  current channel.  

  Sample output:

    @{b}«Ban List»@{ub}  Ban on #killies: *!*@os.freak.com
    @{b}«Ban List»@{ub}  Ban on #killies: JoeUser!juser@iastate.edu
    @{b}«Ban List»@{ub}  End of Ban List for #grapevine.

  See Also: @{"/BANLIST" link BanListCmd}

@endnode

@node CModeItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                      __________________________________
                       @{b}Channel Menu Item: Channel Modes@{ub}
                      ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      Selecting this item will bring up the channel modes window, allowing
  you to view and/or change the modes for the current channel.  If the
  channel mode window is already open, it will be activated and brought
  to the front.

  See Also: @{"/MODE" link ModeCmd}
            @{"Channel Mode Icon" link CModeIcon}
            @{"Channel Mode Window" link CModeWindow}

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Server Menu
@remark ***********************************************************
@node ServerMenu "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                                ______________
                                 @{b} Server Menu@{ub}
                                ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The "Server" menu contains items for controlling the connection to the
  IRC server and server maintenance items for IRC operators.

  @{u}@{b}Menu items@{ub}@{uu}

  @{"Connect           " link ConnectItem} Connect to a server
  @{"Close             " link CloseServerItem} Close connection to the server

  @{"Kill User         " link KillItem} Kill a user

@endnode

@node ConnectItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                         ___________________________
                          @{b}Server Menu Item: Connect@{ub}
                         ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      "Connect" will connect you to an IRC server.  If you are already
  connected to a server, you will be disconnected and reconnected to the
  new server.  A string requester prompts you for a server name.

  See Also: @{"/SERVER" link ServerCmd}

@endnode

@node CloseServerItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                          _________________________
                           @{b}Server Menu Item: Close@{ub}
                          ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      This item will close the connection to the current IRC server.  If
  you are not connected to a server, this option is disabled.

@endnode

@node KillItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                      _____________________________
                       @{b}Server Menu Item: Kill User@{ub}
                      ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      If you are an IRC operator, this menu item will kill the user selected
  in the channel namelist window.  A string requester will be brought up
  asking you to give a reason for the kill.  This item is disabled if you
  are not an IRC operator.

  See Also: @{"/KILL" link KillCmd}@{"/OPER" link OperCmd}

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Personal Menu
@remark ***********************************************************
@node PersonalMenu "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                               ________________
                               @{b} Personal Menu@{ub}
                               ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The "Personal" menu contains items that are related to your status.

  @{u}@{b}Menu items@{ub}@{uu}

  @{"Mark Away " link AwayItem} Toggle your away status

  @{"User Modes" link UModeItem} View and/or set user modes

@endnode

@node AwayItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                       ________________________________
                        @{b}Personal Menu Item: Mark Away@{ub}
                       ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      Enabling this item will cause you to be marked away, using the default
  away message set in the @{"User Config" link UserConfig} window.  Disabling it will remove your
  away status.

  See Also: @{"/AWAY" link AwayCmd}
            @{"Away Icon" link AwayIcon}

@endnode

@node UModeItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                      _________________________________
                       @{b}Personal Menu Item: User Modes@{ub}
                      ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      Selecting this item will bring up the user modes window, allowing
  you to view and/or change your user modes.  If the user mode window is
  already open, it will be activated and brought to the front.

  See Also: @{"/MODE" link ModeCmd}
            @{"User Mode Icon" link UModeIcon}
            @{"User Mode Window" link UModeWindow}

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Misc Menu
@remark ***********************************************************
@node MiscMenu "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                                 ___________
                                  @{b}Misc Menu@{ub}
                                 ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The "Misc" menu contains various items that do not fit in any of the
  other program menus.

  @{u}@{b}Menu items@{ub}@{uu}

  @{"Change Work Directory" link CDItem}

@endnode

@node CDItem "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                   _______________________________________
                    @{b}Misc Menu Item: Change Work Directory@{ub}
                   ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      This menu item brings up an ASL path requester for you to select a new
  work directory.  The work directory is used as the default directory for
  files sent or received through DCC.
      
  See Also: @{"/CD" link CDCmd}@{"/CDREQ" link CDReqCmd}

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Settings Menu
@remark ***********************************************************
@node SettingsMenu "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                             _______________
                              @{b}Settings Menu@{ub}
                             ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The "Settings" menu provides access to many options for customizing
  Grapevine.  All of the options which are set through this menu are
  saved in the settings files.

  @{u}@{b}Menu items@{ub}@{uu}

  @{"Verbose CTCP      " link VerboseCTCP} Display incoming CTCP requests
  @{"Skip MOTD         " link SkipMOTD} Skip server "Message of the Day"
  @{"Confirm Requesters" link ConfReqs} Toggle close/quit confirmation requesters

  @{"Beep on           " link BeepOnMsg} Toggle beeping on receiving messages
  @{"Icon Set          " link IconSet} 4 or 8 color graphic toolbar icons

  @{"Network           " link NetConfig} Server and local host information
  @{"User              " link UserConfig} Personal information
  @{"Display           " link DisplayConfig} Screen and palette control
  @{"Paths             " link PathConfig} Program path setup
  @{"Program           " link ProgConfig} Program operation parameters
  @{"Fonts             " link FontConfig} Various fonts used in the program

  @{"Load/Save/Save As " link Settings} Load and save configuration files

@endnode

@node Settings "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                       __________________________
                        @{b}Grapevine Settings Files@{ub}
                       ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      Grapevine has the ability to load and save configuration files.
  These files contain user preferences which are defined in the @{"settings" link Config 22}
  menu, as well as default channel window position/size, channel window
  zoom position/size, and icon window position.  The following options
  are available for loading and saving settings files:
  
     Save Settings As - Pops up an ASL file save requester to specify the
                        name of the settings file to save.
        Save Settings - Saves settings in the last file which was loaded
                        or saved.
        Load Settings - Prompts the user for the settings file to load.
                        Some of the configuration items will not take
                        effect immediately, notably window orientation
                        and some current network and user information.
                        The latter two can be reset into effect by
                        reconnecting to the server.
@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Network Configuration
@remark ***********************************************************
@node NetConfig "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                     ______________________________
                      @{b}Network Configuration Window@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The network configuration window is where details about your host are
  defined, and where default server information is set.  Each item in the
  window is described below.

  @{b}@{u}User Name@{ub}@{uu}
  Your login username.  If no settings file is found, the environment
  variable USER is read if it exists.

  @{b}@{u}Real Name@{ub}@{uu}
  Your real full name.  Used in your @{"CTCP" link CTCPCmd} FINGER response.
  If no settings file is found, the environment variable REALNAME is read
  if it exists.

  @{b}@{u}Host Name@{ub}@{uu}
  The name of your host.  Also used in the @{"CTCP" link CTCPCmd} FINGER response.
  If no settings file is found, the environment variable HOSTNAME is read
  if it exists.

  The following fields are only available for TCP/IP operation:

  @{b}@{u}Default Server@{ub}@{uu}
  The name of the server to connect to when first running the program.

  @{b}@{u}Server Port@{ub}@{uu}
  Default port number to use when connecting to a server.
  
  @{b}@{u}Server Password@{ub}@{uu}
  Default password to use when connecting to a server.

  @{b}@{u}Autojoin Channel@{ub}@{uu}
  A list of channels to automatically join when first running Grapevine.
  The list is the same format as that of @{"/JOIN" link JoinCmd} arguments, so you can specify
  multiple channels.

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** User Configuration
@remark ***********************************************************
@node UserConfig "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                       ___________________________
                        @{b}User Configuration Window@{ub}
                       ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The user configuration window is where your personal information is
  defined, as well as some default action messages.  Each item in the
  window is described below.
  
  @{b}@{u}Default Nickname@{ub}@{uu}
  @{"Nickname" link NickCmd} to use when first running Grapevine.

  @{b}@{u}DCC Nickname@{ub}@{uu}
  If using serial mode, DCC Nickname is the nickname of a user who can
  receive files for you sent by DCC.  Any DCC requests sent to Grapevine
  will be automatically redirected to the user with this nickname..
  
  @{b}@{u}WhoIs Info@{ub}@{uu}
  Information to be displayed in your @{"/WHOIS" link WhoIsCmd} response.
  
  @{b}@{u}User Info@{ub}@{uu}
  Information to be displayed when a user asks for @{"CTCP" link CTCPCmd} USERINFO from
  you.

  @{b}@{u}Away Message@{ub}@{uu}
  Default message to be used when you mark yourself @{"away" link AwayCmd}.

  @{b}@{u}Kick Message@{ub}@{uu}
  Default message to be displayed when you @{"kick" link KickCmd} a user from a channel.

  @{b}@{u}Quit Message@{ub}@{uu}
  Default message to be displayed when you @{"quit" link QuitCmd} IRC.
@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Display Configuration
@remark ***********************************************************
@node DisplayConfig "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                      ______________________________
                       @{b}Display Configuration Window@{ub}
                      ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      In the display configuration window, the screen on which Grapevine
  will operate is defined.  Each item in the window is described below.
  
  @{b}@{u}Display type@{ub}@{uu}
  Selects the kind of screen Grapevine will open on.  There are four choices
  for this popup gadget:

         Workbench Screen - GV will open on the Workbench screen
    Default Public Screen - GV opens on the default system public screen
                            (normally the Workbench).
      Named Public Screen - GV opens on the public screen with the given.
                            name.  If the named screen is not found when
                            GV attempts to lock it, GV will revert to the
                            default public screen.
     Custom Public Screen - GV will open a new custom screen and make it
                            public.  The public screen name will be
                            "Grapevine.N", where N is some number.  Since
                            the screen is made public, other programs
                            can open their windows on it.

  @{b}@{u}Screen mode@{ub}@{uu}
  If the selected display type is "Custom Public Screen", the screenmode
  is defined here.  Click on the monitor image gadget to open a system
  screenmode requester.

  @{b}@{u}Public screen@{ub}@{uu}
  If the selected display type is "Named Public Screen", the name is
  defined here.  This field must be defined for this display type to
  be accepted.

  @{b}@{u}Edit color@{ub}@{uu}
  If Grapevine is currently running on a custom public screen, selects the
  palette pen to edit the color of.

  @{b}@{u}Red/Green/Blue@{ub}@{uu}
  Slider gadgets to change the RGB values for the currently selected
  palette pen.  The range of values for the sliders is 0-15 on ECS
  machines and 0-255 on AGA or most graphics cards.  Must be running
  on a custom public screen.

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Path Configuration
@remark ***********************************************************
@node PathConfig "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                       ___________________________
                        @{b}Path Configuration Window@{ub}
                       ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      File paths that Grapevine uses to find data and programs are
  defined in this window.  All entries must contain valid paths or
  error requesters will be opened.  If any entries are invalid when
  Grapevine is first run, warning requesters will be opened to inform
  you before problems arise.  Each item in this window is described
  below.
  
  @{b}@{u}DCC program drawer@{ub}@{uu}
  This is the drawer where Grapevine DCC client modules are found.
  If this path is wrong, Grapevine will not be able to find the
  modules and an error will occur if a DCC is attempted or received.

  @{b}@{u}Default work dir@{ub}@{uu}
  This is the default current work directory that will be set on
  program startup.  Files received by DCC will be saved to this
  directory by default.

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Program Configuration
@remark ***********************************************************
@node ProgramConfig "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                      ______________________________
                       @{b}Program Configuration Window@{ub}
                      ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      Various operational program parameters are set in this window.
  Each item is described below.

  @{b}@{u}Scrollback buffer size@{ub}@{uu}
  Sets the size of the text scrollback buffer for each channel window.
  This counts the number of characters in the buffer, and does not
  account for linked list overhead.  Approximately 250 lines of
  average IRC text will be stored per 10K of buffer space.  Default
  is 10K.  Valid range is 8K-250K.

  @{b}@{u}History lines@{ub}@{uu}
  Sets the maximum number of lines to be stored in the command history
  in project window string gadgets.  Default is 50 lines.  Range is
  10-200 lines.

  @{b}@{u}Message spacing@{ub}@{uu}
  Sets the number of pixels to be inserted between different messages
  in the channel window text display.  Inserting a few pixels can help
  make the output more readable.  Default is 2 pixels.  Range is 0-8.

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Font Configuration
@remark ***********************************************************
@node FontConfig "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                       ___________________________
                        @{b}Font Configuration Window@{ub}
                       ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The items in this window allow you to customize the fonts that are
  used by Grapevine.  There are four fonts that can be adjusted.
  
  @{b}@{u}Screen and gadgets@{ub}@{uu}
  This font is used for the screen and window titles on a custom public
  screen and for generic gadget labels on all screens.

  @{b}@{u}Channel text@{ub}@{uu}
  This is a monospaced font that is used to display text in the channel
  text display area.

  @{b}@{u}Channel input gadget@{ub}@{uu}
  This font is for the input string gadget at the bottom of the channel
  windows.  It is used for the label as well as the gadget contents.

  @{b}@{u}Channel namelist@{ub}@{uu}
  The namelist font is used for the listview label and entries in the
  channel namelist window.  It must currently be monospaced.

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Verbose CTCP Menu Item
@remark ***********************************************************
@node VerboseCTCP "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                   ____________________________________
                    @{b}Settings Menu Item: Verbose CTCP@{ub}
                   ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      Enabling verbose CTCP causes all incoming @{"CTCP" link CTCPCmd} requests from other
  users to be displayed.  Ordinarily incoming requests are not displayed.
  Incoming requests will be displayed like the following example:
  
     @{b}«CTCP»@{ub}  Client version info requested by JoeUser.

  This indicates that JoeUser did a "/CTCP yournick VERSION".
  
      Not all incoming CTCPs are displayed in this manner with
  verbose CTCP enabled.  CTCP ACTION messages are displayed as either
  an @{"ACTION" link MeCmd} if the target was a channel or a @{"DESCRIBE" link DescribeCmd} if your nickname
  was the target.  CTCP @{"PING" link PingCmd} messages are not displayed at all.

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Skip MOTD Menu Item
@remark ***********************************************************
@node SkipMOTD "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                     _________________________________
                      @{b}Settings Menu Item: Skip MOTD@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      When you first connect to an IRC server, the server will send a
  welcome message and a few statistics, followed by a "Message of the
  Day" (MOTD).  If the "Skip MOTD" Menu Item is enabled, the MOTD will
  not be displayed.  This option does not affect the @{"/MOTD" link MOTDCmd} command.

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Confirm Requesters Menu Item
@remark ***********************************************************
@node ConfReqs "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                __________________________________________
                 @{b}Settings Menu Item: Confirm Requesters@{ub}
                ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      By default, Grapevine will bring up requesters asking you to confirm
  that you want to perform certain operations--specifically leave channel,
  quit program, and close project.  Enabling this option will prevent such
  requesters from being displayed.  Requesters are never displayed if the
  operation was initiated by string /commands.

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Icon Set Menu Item
@remark ***********************************************************
@node IconSet "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                     ________________________________
                      @{b}Settings Menu Item: Icon Set@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      There are two sets of @{"icons" link Icons} included in Grapevine for the toolbar.
  One set is four-colors, and is suitable for the standard Workbench
  palette.  The other set is an eight-color set which is designed to use
  the 8-color MagicWB palette.
      The 8-color icon set is only available on a screen of at least
  8 colors.  If Grapevine is opened on a 4-color screen, the 4-color icon
  set will be automatically used, and the 8-color option is disabled.

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Beep On Menu Item
@remark ***********************************************************
@node BeepOnMsg "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                __________________________________________
                 @{b}Settings Menu Item: Beep on (Messages)@{ub}
                ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The items in the "Beep on" submenu will cause Grapevine to beep
  the system every time certain kinds of messages arrived.  There are
  three options in this submenu:
  
            Messages - Beep when private @{"messages" link MsgCmd} arrive 
             Notices - Beep when private @{"notices" link MsgCmd} arrive
      Only When Away - Only beep if you are currently marked @{"away" link AwayCmd}.

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Graphic Icon Toolbar
@remark ***********************************************************

@node Icons "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@prev Menus
@next Commands
                            ______________________
                             @{b}Graphic Icon Toolbar@{ub}
                            ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      One of the most useful features of Grapevine is the graphic icon 
  toolbar.  The toolbar consists of roughly a dozen icons which perform
  certain preset actions.  The icons are currently not configurable.
      There are two different icon sets included in Grapevine.  The icon
  icon set is selected in the @{"Settings menu" link IconSet}.
      The selected icon set and the position of the icon window are saved
  in the @{"settings file" link Settings}.

  @{b}@{u}Icons@{ub}@{uu}

   @{"About Program" link AboutIcon} Display program information
   @{"Join         " link JoinIcon} Join channel
   @{"Leave        " link LeaveIcon} Leave channel
   @{"Channel Modes" link CModeIcon} View/set channel modes
   @{"User Modes   " link UModeIcon} View/set user modes
   @{"ChanOp Toggle" link OpIcon} Toggle user chanop status
   @{"Voice Toggle " link VoiceIcon} Toggle user voice status
   @{"Kick User    " link KickIcon} Kick user from channel
   @{"Ban User     " link BanIcon} Ban user from channel
   @{"Who Is User  " link WhoIsIcon} Get information about user
   @{"Ping User    " link PingIcon} Ping user
   @{"Away Toggle  " link AwayIcon} Toggle your away status
   @{"Help         " link HelpIcon} Get help with Grapevine

@endnode

@node AboutIcon "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Icons
                         ____________________________
                          @{b}Description of Icon: About@{ub}
                         ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
     Image: Small bunch of grapes

    Action: Opens a window containing information about Grapevine.

     Notes: If the window is already open it will be activated and moved to
            the front.

  See Also: @{"/ABOUT" link AboutCmd}
            @{"About Menu Item" link AboutItem}

@endnode

@node JoinIcon "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Icons
                         ___________________________
                          @{b}Description of Icon: Join@{ub}
                         ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
     Image: U.S. traffic lane merge symbol (merging arrows)

   Action: Opens a requester prompting for channel to join.

     Notes: Not allowed if the maximum of 10 channels is already joined.

  See Also: @{"/JOIN" link JoinCmd}@{"/LEAVE" link PartCmd}
            @{"Join Menu Item" link JoinItem}

@endnode

@node LeaveIcon "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Icons
                         ____________________________
                          @{b}Description of Icon: Leave@{ub}
                         ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
     Image: U.S. traffic road fork symbol 

    Action: If a channel is joined in the active channel window, that channel
            will be left.

  See Also: @{"/LEAVE" link LeaveCmd}@{"/JOIN" link JoinCmd}
            @{"Leave Menu Item" link LeaveItem}

@endnode

@node CModeIcon "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Icons
                     ____________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Icon: Channel Modes@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
     Image: # sign with triangle "flag" representing mode flags

    Action: Opens the channel mode window.  If the window is already open
            it will be activated and moved to the front.

     Notes: Requires channel operator status

  See Also: @{"/MODE" link ModeCmd}
            @{"Channel Mode Window" link CModeWindow}
            @{"Channel Modes Menu Item" link CModeItem}

@endnode

@node UModeIcon "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Icons
                      _________________________________
                       @{b}Description of Icon: User Modes@{ub}
                      ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
     Image: Human silhouette with triangle "flag"

    Action: Opens the user mode window.  If the window is already open it
            will be activated and moved to the front.

  See Also: @{"/MODE" link ModeCmd}
            @{"User Mode Window" link UModeWindow}
            @{"User Modes Menu Item" link UModeItem}

@endnode

@node OpIcon "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Icons
                          _________________________
                           @{b}Description of Icon: Op@{ub}
                          ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
     Image: Magic wand

    Action: This gadget acts on the currently selected user in the channel
            userlist window, giving that user channel operator privileges.
            If the user is already a channel operator, selecting this icon
            will remove the privileges.

     Notes: Requires channel operator status

  See Also: @{"/OP" link OpCmd}@{/DEOP link DeOpCmd}

@endnode

@node VoiceIcon "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Icons
                         ____________________________
                          @{b}Description of Icon: Voice@{ub}
                         ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
     Image: Human face silhouette with sound waves emanating from mouth

    Action: Gives the currently selected user the ability to speak on a
            moderated channel.

     Notes: Requires channel operator status.

  See Also: @{"/VOICE" link VoiceCmd}@{"/UNVOICE" link UnVoiceCmd}

@endnode

@node KickIcon "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Icons
                       ________________________________
                        @{b}Description of Icon: Kick User@{ub}
                       ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
     Image: Boot

    Action: Kicks the currently selected user from the channel.  If the
            @{"Ask Kick Reason" link AskKickItem} option in the "Settings" menu is enabled,
            a requester is brought up containing the default kick message,
            with the option to change it or cancel.

     Notes: Requires channel operator status

  See Also: @{"/KICK" link KickCmd}
            @{"Kick Menu Item" link KickItem}

@endnode

@node BanIcon "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Icons
                       _______________________________
                        @{b}Description of Icon: Ban User@{ub}
                       ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
     Image: Human silhouette with circle+slash ban symbol

    Action: Bans the currently selected user from the channel.  A requester
            is brought up with a precomposed ban format, with option to
            change and accept or cancel.

     Notes: Requires channel operator status

  See Also: @{"/BAN" link BanCmd}@{"/UNBAN" link UnBanCmd}@{"/BANLIST" link BanListCmd}
            @{"Ban Menu Item" link BanItem}

@endnode

@node WhoIsIcon "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Icons
                      __________________________________
                       @{b}Description of Icon: Who Is User@{ub}
                      ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
     Image: Human silhouette with question mark

    Action: Displays information on the currently selected user.

  See Also: @{"/WHOIS" link WhoIsCmd}@{"/WHOWAS" link WhoWasCmd}@{"/WHO" link WhoCmd}
            @{"Who Is Menu Item" link WhoIsItem}

@endnode

@node PingIcon "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Icons
                       ________________________________
                        @{b}Description of Icon: Ping User@{ub}
                       ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
     Image: Ping pong paddle and ball

    Action: Sends out a message to the currently selected user, which will
            be bounced back.  Upon return, the time elapsed since the ping
            message was sent is displayed.  This gives an indication of how
            much lag is present in the network between users.

  See Also: @{"/PING" link PingCmd}
            @{"Ping Menu Item" link PingItem}

@endnode

@node AwayIcon "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Icons
                      __________________________________
                       @{b}Description of Icon: Toggle Away@{ub}
                      ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
     Image: Zzz bubble

    Action: Marks you as being away from the terminal.  A requester will be
            opened containing the default away message, which can be changed
            or canceled.

  See Also: @{"/AWAY" link AwayCmd}
            @{"Mark Away Menu Item" link AwayItem}

@endnode

@node HelpIcon "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Icons
                         ___________________________
                          @{b}Description of Icon: Help@{ub}
                         ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
     Image: Help bubble

    Action: Activates online help for Grapevine.

  See Also: @{"/HELP" link HelpCmd}

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Input Command Set
@remark ***********************************************************

@node Commands "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@next Registration
@prev Icons
                           ___________________
                            @{b}Input Command Set@{ub}
                           ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      Grapevine features a fairly extensive input command set.  These
  commands are entered in the channel window string gadgets, preceded by
  a /.  All of the implemented commands are listed below, along with a
  quick-reference syntax.

  All of the following commands will also be a part of the ARexx command
  set.  The ARexx interface is planned for the registered release of
  Grapevine.  In addition, these commands are internally used to perform many
  of the operations in the menus and @{"icon toolbar" link Icons}.

    @{b}  Command                         Syntax  @{ub}
    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯  ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    @{" ABOUT    " link AboutCmd    }  /ABOUT
    @{" ADMIN    " link AdminCmd    }  /ADMIN [server]
    @{" AWAY     " link AwayCmd     }  /AWAY [message]
    @{" BAN      " link BanCmd      }  /BAN [channel] pattern [pattern [pattern]]
    @{" BANLIST  " link BanListCmd  }  /BANLIST [channel]
    @{" CD       " link CDCmd       }  /CD [directory]
    @{" CDREQ    " link CDReqCmd    }  /CDREQ [starting path]
    @{" CLEAR    " link ClearCmd    }  /CLEAR [project]
    @{" CLOSEWIN " link CloseWinCmd }  /CLOSEWIN [project]
    @{" CONNECT  " link ConnectCmd  }  /CONNECT targetserver [port [remote server]]
    @{" CTCP     " link CTCPCmd     }  /CTCP nickname[,nickname[,...]] command [arguments]
    @{" DCC      " link DCCCmd      }  /DCC type nickname [arguments...]
    @{" DCCCLR   " link DCCClrCmd   }  /DCCCLR session_number
    @{" DCCLIST  " link DCCListCmd  }  /DCCLIST
    @{" DEOP     " link DeOpCmd     }  /DEOP [channel] nickname [nickname [nickname]]
    @{" DESCRIBE " link DescribeCmd }  /DESCRIBE nickname[,nickname[,...]] text...
    @{" ECHO     " link EchoCmd     }  /ECHO message...
    @{" EXIT     " link QuitCmd     }  /EXIT [message...]
    @{" HELP     " link HelpCmd     }  /HELP [command]
    @{" INFO     " link InfoCmd     }  /INFO [server]
    @{" ISON     " link IsOnCmd     }  /ISON nickname [nickname [...]]
    @{" INVITE   " link InviteCmd   }  /INVITE nickname [channel]
    @{" JOIN     " link JoinCmd     }  /JOIN channel[,channel[,...]] [key[,key[,...]]
    @{" KICK     " link KickCmd     }  /KICK [channel] nickname [reason...]
    @{" KILL     " link KillCmd     }  /KILL nickname reason...
    @{" LEAVE    " link LeaveCmd    }  /LEAVE [channel[,channel[,...]]]
    @{" LINKS    " link LinksCmd    }  /LINKS [[remote server] servermask]]
    @{" LIST     " link ListCmd     }  /LIST channel[,channel[,...]] [server]
    @{" LUSERS   " link LUsersCmd   }  /LUSERS [server]
    @{" ME       " link MeCmd       }  /ME text...
    @{" MODE     " link ModeCmd     }  /MODE [channel] ±mode [arguments...]
    @{" MOTD     " link MOTDCmd     }  /MOTD [server]
    @{" MSG      " link MsgCmd      }  /MSG nickname[,nickname[,...]] message...
    @{" NAMES    " link NamesCmd    }  /NAMES [channel[,channel[,...]]]
    @{" NICK     " link NickCmd     }  /NICK nickname
    @{" NOTICE   " link NoticeCmd   }  /NOTICE nickname[,nickname[,...]] message...
    @{" OP       " link OpCmd       }  /OP [channel] nickname [nickname [nickname]]
    @{" OPENWIN  " link OpenWinCmd  }  /OPENWIN
    @{" OPER     " link OperCmd     }  /OPER user password
    @{" PART     " link LeaveCmd    }  /PART [channel]
    @{" PING     " link PingCmd     }  /PING [nickname | channel]
    @{" QUERY    " link QueryCmd    }  /QUERY [nickname]
    @{" QUIT     " link QuitCmd     }  /QUIT [message...]
    @{" RAW      " link RawCmd      }  /RAW command...
    @{" REHASH   " link RehashCmd   }  /REHASH
    @{" RESTART  " link RestartCmd  }  /RESTART
    @{" SAY      " link SayCmd      }  /SAY message...
    @{" SERVER   " link ServerCmd   }  /SERVER [server [port] [password]]]
    @{" SIGN     " link QuitCmd     }  /SIGN [message...]
    @{" SIGNOFF  " link QuitCmd     }  /SIGNOFF [message...]
    @{" SQUIT    " link SQuitCmd    }  /SQUIT server reason...
    @{" STATS    " link StatsCmd    }  /STATS [query [server]]
    @{" SUMMON   " link SummonCmd   }  /SUMMON username [server]
    @{" TIME     " link TimeCmd     }  /TIME [server | nickname]
    @{" TOPIC    " link TopicCmd    }  /TOPIC [channel[,channel[,...]]] [topic...]
    @{" TRACE    " link TraceCmd    }  /TRACE [server | nickname]
    @{" UNBAN    " link UnBanCmd    }  /UNBAN [channel] pattern1 [pattern2 [pattern3]]
    @{" UNVOICE  " link UnVoiceCmd  }  /UNVOICE [channel] nickname [nickname [nickname]]
    @{" VERSION  " link VersionCmd  }  /VERSION [server | nickname]
    @{" VOICE    " link VoiceCmd    }  /VOICE [channel] nickname [nickname [nickname]]
    @{" WALLOPS  " link WallOpsCmd  }  /WALLOPS message...
    @{" WHO      " link WhoCmd      }  /WHO [nickname | channel | mask] ["o"]
    @{" WHOIS    " link WhoIsCmd    }  /WHOIS [server] nickname[,nickname[,...]]
    @{" WHOWAS   " link WhoWasCmd   }  /WHOWAS nickname[,nickname[,...]] [count [server]]
@endnode

@node AboutCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    _____________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: ABOUT@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /ABOUT

    Action: Opens a window containing information about Grapevine. If the
            About window is already open it will be activated and moved to
            the front.

  See Also: @{"About Icon" link AboutIcon}
            @{"About Menu Item" link AboutItem}
@endnode

@node AdminCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    _____________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: ADMIN@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /ADMIN [server]

    Action: Displays administrative information on the server. If server
            is not specified, the current server is assumed.

   Example: /ADMIN ircserver.iastate.edu
@endnode

@node AwayCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    _____________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: AWAY@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /AWAY [message]

    Action: Marks you as being away from the terminal.  If message is
            specified, it will be used; otherwise the default away message
            set in the @{"User Configuration" link UserConfig} window will be used.  If no
            message is given but you are already marked away, away status
            will be removed.

   Example: /AWAY I went to give my poor dog a bone.  Try me later.

  See Also: @{"Away Icon" link AwayIcon}
            @{"Mark Away Menu Item" link AwayItem}
@endnode

@node BanCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ___________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: BAN@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /BAN [channel] nick!user@host [nick!user@host [nick!user@host]]

    Action: Places a ban on the current channel, using the specified pattern
            Wildcards may be used, and up to three bans may be specified. If
            a ban is already in place on the channel which supercedes the
            specified pattern, the new ban will not be placed.  Most
            IRC servers enforce a limit of 20 bans on a channel.  

            Same as "/MODE +b nick!user@host".

     Notes: Requires channel operator status.

   Example: /BAN JoeUser!juser@some.site.com
            /BAN #ghoul *!juser@*.com

  See Also: @{"/UNBAN" link UnBanCmd}@{"/BANLIST" link BanListCmd}@{"/MODE" link ModeCmd}
            @{"Ban Icon" link BanIcon}
            @{"Ban Menu Item" link BanItem}
@endnode

@node BanListCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                   _______________________________________
                    @{b}Description of Input Command: BANLIST@{ub}
                   ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /BANLIST [channel]

    Action: Lists the current bans on the specified channel, or the current
            channel if none is supplied.

  See Also: @{"/BAN" link BanCmd}@{"/UNBAN" link UnBanCmd}@{"/MODE" link ModeCmd}
            @{"List Bans Menu Item" link BanListItem}
@endnode

@node CDCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                      __________________________________
                       @{b}Description of Input Command: CD@{ub}
                      ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /CD [path]

    Action: Changes the current directory.  Files received by DCC will go
            to this directory.
          
   Example: /CD Work:Grapevine/dccfiles

  See Also: @{"/CDREQ" link CDReqCmd}
            @{"Change Work Dir Menu Item" link CDItem}
@endnode

@node CDReqCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    _____________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: CDREQ@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /CDREQ [starting path]

    Action: Brings up an ASL drawer requester for the user to select a new
            current directory.  Files received by DCC will go to this
            directory.
          
   Example: /CDREQ Work:

  See Also: @{"/CD" link CDCmd}
            @{"Change Work Dir Menu Item" link CDItem}
@endnode

@node ClearCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    _____________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: CLEAR@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /CLEAR [project]

    Action: Clears the scrollback buffer in the specified project window.
            If no project is specified, the buffer for the current window
            is cleared.
          
  See Also: @{"Clear Buffer Menu Item" link ClearItem}
@endnode

      The Clear Buffer menu option clears all lines in the scrollback buffer
  of the active channel window.  There is no confirmation for this item.

@node CloseWinCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                   ________________________________________
                    @{b}Description of Input Command: CLOSEWIN@{ub}
                   ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /CLOSEWIN [project]

    Action: Closes the specified project window, or if not specified, will
            close the active window.  Closing the last project will quit
            the program.

   Example: /CLOSEWIN 2

  See Also: @{"/OPENWIN" link OpenWinCmd}
            @{"Close Menu Item" link CloseItem}
@endnode

@node ConnectCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                   _______________________________________
                    @{b}Description of Input Command: CONNECT@{ub}
                   ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /CONNECT targetserver [port [remote server]]

    Action: Connects the remote server to the target server.  If no remote
            server is specified, the current server is assumed.  Port
            defaults to 6667.

     Notes: Requires IRC operator status.

   Example: /CONNECT eff.org
            /CONNECT csz.bu.edu 6667 irc.iastate.edu

  See Also: @{"/SQUIT" link SQuitCmd}@{/OPER link OperCmd}
@endnode

@node CTCPCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ____________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: CTCP@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /CTCP nickname[,nickname[,...]] command [arguments]

    Action: Client-To-Client Protocol.  CTCP sends specialized messages
            to another client or to all clients in a channel.

            Most clients support the CLIENTINFO command which will display
            a list of the available CTCP commands.  Standard CTCP commands
            which are supported include TIME, FINGER, VERSION, and USERINFO.

            If a channel is specified instead of nickname, the CTCP message
            will be sent to all users on that channel.

   Example: /CTCP JaneUser VERSION
            /CTCP JoeUser CLIENTINFO
@endnode

@node DCCCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ___________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: DCC@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /DCC type nickname [arguments...]

    Action: Initiates a DCC to another user.  The kind of DCC is specified
            by the "type" parameter.  Grapevine will load an external program
            to handle the DCC request, named "DCC.<type>" (e.g., "DCC.Send").
            Any extra arguments depend on the specific DCC program being
            called, so refer to the documentation to that program for
            appropriate parameters.

   Example: /DCC SEND JoeUser
            /DCC CHAT JaneUser

     Notes: Disabled in serial mode.

  See Also: @{"/DCCCLR" link DCCClrCmd}@{"/DCCLIST" link DCCListCmd}
@endnode

@node DCCClrCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    ______________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: DCCCLR@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /DCCCLR session_number

    Action: Removes the specified session number from the DCC list.
            Note that this does NOT actually cancel a DCC session.
            It is useful for removing sessions if a DCC client dies
            before it can send a completion message to Grapevine.
            It is unnecessary to include the leading zeros in the
            session number.

   Example: /DCCCLR 7

  See Also: @{"/DCC" link DCCCmd}@{"/DCCLIST" link DCCListCmd}
@endnode

@node DCCListCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                   _______________________________________
                    @{b}Description of Input Command: DCCLIST@{ub}
                   ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /DCCLIST

    Action: Displays a list of DCC sessions currently waiting or active.

  See Also: @{"/DCC" link DCCCmd}@{"/DCCCLR" link DCCClrCmd}
@endnode

@node DeOpCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ____________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: DEOP@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /DEOP [channel] nickname [nickname [nickname]]

    Action: Removes channel operator privileges from one to three nicknames
            in the current channel. You must be a channel operator in
            order to use this command.

            Same as "/MODE -o nickname".

   Example: /DEOP JoeUser

     Notes: Requires channel operator status.

  See Also: @{"/OP" link OpCmd}@{"/MODE" link ModeCmd}
            @{"ChanOp Icon" link OpIcon}
@endnode

@node DescribeCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                   ________________________________________
                    @{b}Description of Input Command: DESCRIBE@{ub}
                   ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /DESCRIBE nickname[,nickname[,...]] text...

   Aliases: /DESC

    Action: Sends a message to the specified user(s) as an action
            description.  Same as "/CTCP nickname ACTION text..."

   Example: /DESCRIBE JaneUser throws an onion ring across the room.

  See Also: @{"/CTCP" link CTCPCmd}@{"/ME" link MeCmd}
@endnode

@node EchoCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ____________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: ECHO@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /ECHO message...

    Action: Displays the given message in the current window.  No text
            is sent to the IRC server.

   Example: /ECHO This is only a test.
@endnode

@node HelpCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ____________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: HELP@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /HELP [command]

    Action: Displays online help for the specified command, or if no command
            is specified, displays a list of all commands for which help
            is available.

   Example: /HELP notice

  See Also: @{"Help Icon" link HelpIcon}
@endnode

@node InfoCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ____________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: INFO@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /INFO [server]

    Action: Displays information on the authors, testers, and other
            contributors for the specified IRC server.  If no server is
            specified, the current server is assumed.

   Example: /INFO eff.org
@endnode

@node IsOnCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ____________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: ISON@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /ISON nickname [nickname [...]]

    Action: When given a list of nicknames, returns a list of those
            nicknames that are on IRC at the given time.

   Example: /ISON JaneUser JoeUser
@endnode

@node InviteCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    ______________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: INVITE@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /INVITE nickname [channel]

    Action: Invites a user to join the specified channel, or if none is
            specified, invites the user to the channel joined in the
            active window.

     Notes: Requires channel operator status if the channel is open by
            invitation only.

   Example: /INVITE JoeUser #irchelp
@endnode

@node JoinCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ____________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: JOIN@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /JOIN channel[,channel[,...]] [key[,key[,...]]]

   Aliases: /J

    Action: Join a channel, using the specified key if provided.  If the
            channel does not exist, a new channel with that name will be
            created.  If no channel is joined in the active window, then
            the join will take place in that window.  Otherwise, a new
            channel window will be automatically opened for the channel.
            A maximum of 10 channels may be joined simultaneously.

     Notes: If you specify a list of channels to join, where one of the
            channels later in the list requires a key but the preceding
            channels do not, you still need to specify a key for the first
            channels.  The garbage keys will be ignored by the server.

   Example: /JOIN #amiga
            /JOIN #hazard,#jinx foobar,syrinx
                  · Join #hazard with key "foobar", #jinx with key "syrinx".)

  See Also: @{"/LEAVE" link LeaveCmd}
            @{"Join Icon" link JoinIcon}
            @{"Join Menu Item" link JoinItem}

@endnode

@node KickCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ____________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: KICK@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /KICK [channel] nickname [reason...]

    Action: Kicks the user off of the given channel.  If no channel is
            specified, kicks the user off the current channel. If no reason
            is supplied, the default kick message defined in the
            @{"User Configuration" link UserConfig} window will be used.

     Notes: Requires channel operator status.

   Example: /KICK JaneUser
            /KICK #jail JoeUser Do not pass GO, do not collect $200.

  See Also: @{"/BAN" link BanCmd}
            @{"Kick Icon" link KickIcon}
            @{"Kick Menu Item" link KickItem}
@endnode

@node KillCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ____________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: KILL@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /KILL nickname reason...

    Action: Terminates the specified user's connection to IRC.  A reason
            for the KILL must be specified.  No default is provided.


   Example: /KILL JoeUser Avoiding channel bans.

  See Also: @{"/OPER" link OperCmd}
            @{"Kill Menu Item" link KillItem}
@endnode

@node LeaveCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    _____________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: LEAVE@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /LEAVE [channel[,channel[,...]]]

   Aliases: /L, /PART

    Action: Leaves the specified channel, if joined.  If no channel is
            supplied, leaves the channel joined in the active window.

     Notes: Requires channel operator status

   Example: /LEAVE #jail

  See Also: @{"/JOIN" link JoinCmd}
            @{"Leave Icon" link LeaveIcon}
@endnode

@node LinksCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    _____________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: LINKS@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /LINKS [[remote server] servermask]]

    Action: Display a list of all servers connected to the IRC network.
            If the servermask is specified, all servers with that mask
            will be displayed.  If remote server is specified, the link
            information is obtained from that server.

   Example: /LINKS *.org
@endnode

@node ListCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    ____________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: LIST@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /LIST channel[,channel[,...]] [server]

    Action: Displays information on the specified channel if currently
            existing and visible.  If "**" is specified as the channel,
            a complete list of all visible channels will be displayed.
            WARNING!  The complete list is VERY long, so use this with
            extreme discretion!  If server is specified, the channel
            information will be obtained from that server.

   Example: /LIST #garbage
            /LIST #earth eff.org
@endnode

@node LUsersCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    ______________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: LUSERS@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /LUSERS [servermask] [server]

    Action: Display information on the current number of visible and
            invisible users, number of servers, and number of operators
            currently connected to IRC.  If servermask is specified,
            total statistics for matching servers will be listed.  If
            server is supplied, information will come from that server.

   Example: /LUSERS *.edu irc.iastate.edu
@endnode

@node MeCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                      __________________________________
                       @{b}Description of Input Command: ME@{ub}
                      ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /ME text...

    Action: Displays a message to the current channel as an Action.
            Same as "/CTCP #channel ACTION text..."

     Notes: If you are in QUERY mode, /ME will act as a /DESCRIBE.

   Example: /ME throws an onion ring across the room.

  See Also: @{"/CTCP" link CTCPCmd}@{"/DESCRIBE" link DescribeCmd}@{"/QUERY" link QueryCmd}
@endnode

@node ModeCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ____________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: MODE@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /MODE [channel | yournickname] ±mode [arguments...]

    Action: Changes the modes for the specified channel or your user
            modes.  The channel modes are briefly listed below:
           
              t - Topic changing only by channel operators
              n - No messages to channel allowed unless user is joined
              p - Private channel
              s - Secret channel
              i - Joining allowed by invitation only
              m - Moderated (only users with chanop and voice may speak)
              l - Limit maximum number of users in channel
              k - Keyword required to join channel
              v - Set voice status for specified user
              o - Set channel operator status for specified user
              b - Place a ban with the specified mask
           
            User modes are as follows:
           
              w - Receive WALLOPS
              s - Receive kill notices from server
              i - Invisible
              o - IRC operator status (may not be set, only removed)

            For more detailed descriptions of these modes, refer to the
            documentation on the channel and user mode windows.

     Notes: Changing channel modes requires channel operator status.

   Example: /MODE #booray +l 30
            /MODE JaneUser -s+i
            /MODE +b *!juser@*.com

  See Also: @{"Channel Mode Window" link CModeWindow}@{"User Mode Window" link UModeWindow}
            @{"/BAN" link BanCmd}@{"/UNBAN" link UnBanCmd}@{"/OP" link OpCmd}@{"/DEOP" link DeOpCmd}@{"/VOICE" link VoiceCmd}@{"/UNVOICE" link UnVoiceCmd}
            @{"Channel Modes Menu Item" link CModeItem}@{"User Modes Menu Item" link UModeItem}
@endnode

@node MOTDCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ____________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: MOTD@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /MOTD [server]

    Action: Displays the message of the day for the specified server,
            or the current server if none is supplied.  This command is
            not affected by the @{"Skip MOTD" link SkipMOTD} option in the "Settings" menu..

   Example: /MOTD irc-2.mit.edu
@endnode

@node MSGCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ___________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: MSG@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /MSG nickname[,nickname[,...]] message...

   Aliases: /M

    Action: Sends a private message to the specified nickname(s).  If the
            nickname is a channel name, it is equivalent to a public
            message to the channel.

            Sending a message to "," will send to the last person who sent
            you a message or notice.

            Sending a message to "." will send to the last person you sent
            a message or notice to.

   Example: /MSG JoeUser Hi there!

  See Also: @{"/NOTICE" link NoticeCmd}@{"/QUERY" link QueryCmd}
@endnode

@node NamesCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    _____________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: NAMES@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /NAMES [channel[,channel[,...]]]

    Action: Displays a list of usernames on the specified channel, or the
            current channel if none given.  If channel is "**", a list of
            users on all IRC channels will be displayed. WARNING!  The
            complete user list is VERY long.  Use with extreme discretion!

            If the names list applies to a currently joined window, the
            namelist window will be refreshed, or automatically opened if
            it was closed.

   Example: /NAMES #antfarm

  See Also: @{"/WHO" link WhoCmd}
            @{"Names Menu Item" link NamesItem}
@endnode

@node NickCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    ____________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: NICK@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /NICK nickname

    Action: Changes your nickname to that specified.  If the nickname is
            taken or is otherwise illegal, your nickname will revert back
            to what it was before issuing the /NICK command.
           
            Nicknames may only consist of characters 0-9, A-Z, and any of
            the following: [\]^_`{|}.  Nicknames may not begin with a
            number.  As a matter of etiquette, nicknames should consist only
            of alphanumeric characters and not the symbols, with the
            exception of _, which is often used in place of spaces.

   Example: /NICK JaneUser
@endnode

@node NoticeCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    ______________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: NOTICE@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /NOTICE nickname[,nickname[,...]] message...

    Action: Sends a private notice to the specified nickname(s).  If the
            nickname is a channel name, it is similar to a public message
            to the channel.

            Sending a notice to "," will send to the last person who sent
            you a message or notice.

            Sending a notice to "." will send to the last person you sent
            a message or notice to.

   Example: /NOTICE JaneUser Let me know if you feel like singing a song.

  See Also: @{"/MSG" link MsgCmd}
@endnode

@node OpCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                      __________________________________
                       @{b}Description of Input Command: OP@{ub}
                      ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /OP [channel] nickname1 [nickname2 [nickname3]]

    Action: Gives channel operator privileges to the specified user(s).  
            You must be a channel operator in order to issue this command.

            Equivalent to "/MODE +o nickname".

     Notes: Requires channel operator status.

   Example: /OP JoeUser JaneUser

  See Also: @{"/DEOP" link DeOpCmd}@{"/MODE" link ModeCmd}
            @{"ChanOp Icon" link OpIcon}
@endnode

@node OpenWinCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                   _______________________________________
                    @{b}Description of Input Command: OPENWIN@{ub}
                   ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /OPENWIN

    Action: Opens a new channel window if fewer than 10 windows are already
            opened.

  See Also: @{"/CLOSEWIN" link CloseWinCmd}
            @{"New Window Menu Item" link NewWindowItem}
@endnode

@node OperCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ____________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: OPER@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /OPER user password

    Action: Request IRC operator status from the current server as the
            specified user with the given password.  Both arguments
            must be supplied.

   Example: /OPER JaneUser knightme

  See Also: @{"/CONNECT" link ConnectCmd}@{"/KILL" link KillCmd}@{"/REHASH" link RehashCmd}@{"/SQUIT" link SQuitCmd}@{"/RESTART" link RestartCmd}
@endnode

@node PingCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ____________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: PING@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /PING nickname[,nickname[,...]]

    Action: Sends out a message to the currently selected user, which will
            be bounced back.  Upon return, the time elapsed since the ping
            message was sent is displayed.  This gives an indication of how
            much lag is present in the network between users.  If a channel
            is specified instead of a nickname, ping message will be sent to
            all users in that channel.

   Example: /PING JoeUser
            /PING #orbit

  See Also: @{"Ping Icon" link PingIcon}
            @{"Ping Menu Item" link PingItem}
@endnode

@node QueryCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    _____________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: QUERY@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /QUERY [nickname]
            
    Action: /QUERY will force all normal input in the current window to be
            sent to the specified nickname as if you had typed "/MSG
            nickname" to send a private message.  Furthermore, a /ME will
            be treated as a /DESCRIBE.  If you are joined to a channel in
            the current window, you will have to turn off query mode or
            send a /MSG to the channel.  Typing /QUERY with no arguments
            will turn query mode off.

  See Also: @{"/MSG" link MsgCmd}@{"/ME" link MeCmd}@{"/DESCRIBE" link DescribeCmd}
            @{"Query Menu Item" link QueryItem}
@endnode

@node QuitCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ____________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: QUIT@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /QUIT [message...]
            
   Aliases: /BYE, /EXIT, /SIGN, /SIGNOFF

    Action: Closes the connection to the server and exits Grapevine.  If
            message is supplied, it will be displayed in your signoff
            message to all channels to which you were joined.  Otherwise
            the default quit message defined in the @{"User Configuration" link UserConfig}
            window will be used.

   Example: /QUIT Hasta la vista, baby!

  See Also: @{"Quit Menu Item" link QuitItem}
@endnode

@node RawCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ___________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: RAW@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /RAW command...

    Action: Sends a raw IRC command to the server without parsing.  Raw IRC
            messages are defined in the IRC protocol outline the RFC #1459
            (Request For Comments) file.  This RFC is available in
            Amigaguide format on the Grapevine support site.

   Example: /RAW PRIVMSG #jello :This is a test message.
@endnode

@node RehashCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    ______________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: REHASH@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /REHASH

    Action: Force the server you are on to reread its configuration file.

     Notes: Requires IRC operator status.

  See Also: @{"/RESTART" link RestartCmd}@{"/OPER" link OperCmd}
@endnode

@node RestartCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                   _______________________________________
                    @{b}Description of Input Command: RESTART@{ub}
                   ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /RESTART

    Action: Force the server you are on to restart itself.

     Notes: Requires IRC operator status.

  See Also: @{"/REHASH" link RehashCmd}@{"/OPER" link OperCmd}
@endnode

@node SayCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ___________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: SAY@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /SAY message...

    Action: Sends a public message to the current channel.  Just like typing
            text in a normal channel window with no command.  This command is
            useful for sending a message to the channel while in @{"/QUERY" link QueryCmd}
            mode.

   Example: /SAY This is only a test.
@endnode

@node ServerCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    ______________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: SERVER@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /SERVER [server [port] [password]]]

    Action: Closes the connection to the current server and connects to the
            specified server.  Port and password are optional.  If not
            supplied, the current port number and password will be used.
            If no server is given, the current server will be displayed.

     Notes: Grapevine is NOT compatible with version 2.7 servers. If you have
            problems using a server, make sure it is version 2.8 or newer.
            You can check the server version with the @{"/VERSION" link VersionCmd} command.

            A complete list of operational IRC servers is available on the
            @{"Grapevine support" link Support} site.

   Example: /SERVER uni-paderborn.de 6667

  See Also: @{"Connect Menu Item" link ConnectItem}@{"Close Server Menu Item" link CloseServerItem}
@endnode

@node SQuitCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    _____________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: SQUIT@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /SQUIT server reason...

    Action: Close connection of specified server from the IRC network..
            A reason must be supplied.  No default is provided.

     Notes: Requires IRC operator status.

   Example: /SQUIT eff.org Rerouting server connections.

  See Also: @{"/CONNECT" link ConnectCmd}@{"/OPER" link OperCmd}
@endnode

@node StatsCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    _____________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: STATS@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /STATS c|h|k|i|l|m|u|y [server]

    Action: Display selected usage statistics on the specified IRC server,
            or the current server if none is specified.  Statistics which
            may be obtained are:

              c: Lists the names of the servers that are allowed to connect
                 to the server (C and N lines).
              h: Lists the hubs and leaves of the server (H and L lines).
              k: Lists the servers which are not allowed to connect to this
                 server (K lines).
              i: Lists the servers which can connect to this server
                 (I lines).
              l: Displays throughput statistics for the sever.
              m: Display a count of the times various commands were used.
              o: List the authorized operators of this server.
              u: Display the uptime for the server.
              y: List connection classes for the server (Y lines).

   Example: /STATS u irc.iastate.edu
@endnode

@node SummonCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    ______________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: SUMMON@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /SUMMON username [server]

    Action: Attempt to summon a user to IRC.  This command is not supported
            on all servers.

   Example: /SUMMON juser irc.colorado.edu
@endnode

@node TimeCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ____________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: TIME@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /TIME [server | nickname]

    Action: Displays the current time on the specified server, or on the
            server to which a specified user is connected.

   Example: /TIME JoeUser
            /TIME irc.indiana.edu
@endnode

@node TopicCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    _____________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: TOPIC@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /TOPIC [channel] [topic...]

    Action: Set the topic for the specified channel.  If no channel is
            specified, the current channel will be used.  If no topic is
            specified, the current topic for the channel will be displayed.

   Example: /TOPIC This is a mess.
            /TOPIC #appletree
@endnode

@node TraceCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    _____________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: TRACE@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /TRACE [server | nickname]

    Action: Displays the servers connected between your server an the
            specified server (or the server to which a specified user is
            connected) and lists all of the servers which are connected
            to the one specified.  If no server is given, all servers
            connected to the current server are listed.

   Example: /TRACE irc-2.mit.edu
@endnode

@node UnBanCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    _____________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: UNBAN@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /UNBAN [channel] nick!user@host [nick!user@host [nick!user@host]]

    Action: Removes the specified ban(s) on the current channel.  You must
            be a channel operator to use this command.

            Same as "/MODE -b nick!user@host".

     Notes: Requires channel operator status.

   Example: /UNBAN *!juser@*.com

  See Also: @{"/BAN" link BanCmd}@{"/BANLIST" link BanListCmd}@{"/MODE" link ModeCmd}
@endnode

@node UnVoiceCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                   _______________________________________
                    @{b}Description of Input Command: UNVOICE@{ub}
                   ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /UNVOICE [channel] nickname1 [nickname2 [nickname3]]

    Action: Removes voice privileges from one or more nicknames in the
            current channel. You must be a channel operator in order to use
            this command.

            Same as "/MODE -v nickname".

     Notes: Requires channel operator status.

   Example: /UNVOICE JaneUser

  See Also: @{"/VOICE" link VoiceCmd}@{"/MODE" link ModeCmd}
            @{"Voice Icon" link VoiceIcon}
@endnode

@node VersionCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                   _______________________________________
                    @{b}Description of Input Command: VERSION@{ub}
                   ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /VERSION [server | nickname]

    Action: Displays the version of the specified server or server to which
            the specified user is connected.  If no server is given, the
            current server is assumed.

  Example: /VERSION irc-2.mit.edu
@endnode

@node VoiceCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    _____________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: VOICE@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /VOICE [channel] nickname1 [nickname2 [nickname3]]

    Action: Gives voice privileges to one or more nicknames in the current
            channel.  Only channel operators and users with voice may speak
            on a moderated channel.  You must be a channel operator in order
            to use this command.

            Same as "/MODE +v nickname".

     Notes: Requires channel operator status.

   Example: /VOICE JoeUser

  See Also: @{"/UNVOICE" link UnVoiceCmd}@{"/MODE" link ModeCmd}
            @{"Voice Icon" link VoiceIcon}
@endnode

@node WAllOpsCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                   _______________________________________
                    @{b}Description of Input Command: WALLOPS@{ub}
                   ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /WALLOPS message...

    Action: Broadcasts a message to all IRC operators online.  Since this
            command was widely abused in the past, many servers will not
            support it.

     Notes: Requires IRC operator status.

   Example: /WALLOPS Disconnecting server eff.org for maintenance.

  See Also: @{"/OPER" link OperCmd}

@endnode

@node WhoCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                     ___________________________________
                      @{b}Description of Input Command: WHO@{ub}
                     ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /WHO [nickname | username | host | server | channel | mask] ["o"]

    Action: Gives a detailed listing of a specified user, all users on a
            channel, or all users matching a wildcard mask.  The mask
            applies to hostnames as well as server names.  "/WHO *" will
            list the users in the channel that you @{b}most recently joined@{ub}.
            "/WHO **" will list all users on IRC (LONG).

            If "o" is specified at the end of the line, only matching users
            who are IRC operators will be listed.  "/WHO ** o" will list all
            operators currently online.

            /WHO will take multiple target arguments separated by commas.

     Notes: There is a bug in some older 2.8 servers which will cause
            them to close the connection part way through a complete /WHO
            listing.  This is not a bug in Grapevine.

   Example: /WHO #bottub
            /WHO *.nixon.gov
            /WHO JoeUser,JaneUser

  See Also: @{"/NAMES" link NamesCmd}@{"/WHOIS" link WhoIsCmd}@{"/WHOWAS" link WhoWasCmd}
            @{"Names Menu Item" link NamesItem}
@endnode

@node WhoIsCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    _____________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: WHOIS@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /WHOIS [server] nickname[,nickname[,nickname[,...]]]

    Action: Displays detailed information for a particular user(s).  If
            server is specified, that server will be queried for the
            information.

   Example: /WHOIS JaneUser
            /WHOIS irc.iastate.edu JoeUser,JaneUser

  See Also: @{"/WHOWAS" link WhoWasCmd}@{"/WHO" link WhoCmd}@{"/NAMES" link NamesCmd}
            @{"Who Is Icon" link WhoIsIcon}
            @{"Who Is Menu Item" link WhoIsItem}
@endnode

@node WhoWasCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    ______________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: WHOWAS@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /WHOWAS nickname[,nickname[,...]] [count [server]]

    Action: Attempt to display personal information on a user which is
            no longer on IRC.  If count is specified, only the last 'count'
            occurrences of the user will be shown.  If server is specified,
            it will be queried for the desired information.

   Example: /WHOWAS JoeUser

  See Also: @{"/WHOIS" link WhoIsCmd}@{"/WHO" link WhoCmd}@{"/NAMES" link NamesCmd}
@endnode

@node WhoWasCmd "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@toc Commands
                    ______________________________________
                     @{b}Description of Input Command: WINDOW@{ub}
                    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
    Syntax: /WINDOW projectnum

    Action: Makes projectnum the currently active window.

   Example: /WINDOW 1
@endnode

@node CModeWindow "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                            _____________________
                             @{b}Channel Mode Window@{ub}
                            ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      The channel mode window provides an easy way to adjust any number
  of channel modes without having to worry about cryptic mode flags.  All
  of the channel modes are represented by the gadgets detailed below.
  Note that you will not be allowed to set channel modes if you are not a
  channel operator--the "Use" button will be disabled.

  @{b}@{u}Topic Protection@{ub}@{uu}
  If this mode is set, only channel operators are allowed to set the @{"topic" link TopicCmd}.
  This offers some protection from abuse of topic changes.

  @{b}@{u}No Messaging@{ub}@{uu}
  This mode prevents users who are not members of a channel from sending
  messages to the channel.  Without this mode, a user could flood the
  channel with messages even after they had been @{"kicked" link KickCmd} and/or @{banned link BanCmd}.

  @{b}@{u}Moderated@{ub}@{uu}
  On a moderated channel, public discussion is limited to those channel
  operators and those users who are given @{"voice" link VoiceCmd} privileges.  No other
  users are allowed to send messages to the channel.

  @{b}@{u}Private@{ub}@{uu}
  Private channels are not different than a normal channel except that they
  may appear in the channel list as "Prv" with no topic, users on the
  channel are not shown to be on that channel in a @{"/WHOIS" link WhoIsCmd} reply, and  a
  @{"/NAMES" link NamesCmd} request will not list users on the channel, unless the querying
  user is also a member of the channel. A channel which is private cannot
  also be secret.

  @{b}@{u}Secret@{ub}@{uu}
  Secret channels are similar to private channels except that they do not
  appear at all in the channel list unless the querying user is also a
  member of the channel.  A channel which is secret cannot also be private.

  @{b}@{u}Invite Only@{ub}@{uu}
  A channel with this mode set may only be joined if the user has been
  invited with the @{"/INVITE" link InviteCmd} command.  No other users are allowed to join.

  @{b}@{u}Limit Users@{ub}@{uu}
  With this mode set, a limit is placed on the maximum number of users
  that may be joined simultaneously.  If the channel is full and a user
  attempts to @{"join" link JoinCmd}, the user will be refused entry. Enter
  the limit on the number of users in the accompanying integer gadget.
  A user limit of zero is not allowed.

  @{b}@{u}Keyword Lock@{ub}@{uu}
  If a keyword is in place on a channel, only users who supply the proper
  keyword in the @{"/JOIN" link JoinCmd} command will be allowed access.  Users who
  do not supply the proper keyword will be refused access.  Keywords may
  be a maximum of 23 characters, and empty keywords are not allowed.

  @{b}See Also:@{ub} @{"/MODE" link ModeCmd}@{"User Mode Window" link UModeWindow}
@endnode

@node UModeWindow "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
                              __________________
                               @{b}User Mode Window@{ub}
                              ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      User modes determines how you appear to other users, and determines
  whether certain types messages are sent to your client.  You may change
  your user mode at any time, and if you at any time change @{"servers" link ServerCmd}, your
  user modes will be carried over to the new server.

  @{b}@{u}WALLOPS visible@{ub}@{uu}
  This mode determines whether WALLOPS messages are sent to you.  WALLOPS
  are messages which are sent to all operators on IRC.

  @{b}@{u}Server Notices@{ub}@{uu}
  If this mode is set, you will receive notices from the server whenever
  another user is killed and other messages which may be of concern to
  IRC operators.

  @{b}@{u}Invisible@{ub}@{uu}
  If you are marked as invisible, you will not be shown in a @{"/NAMES" link NamesCmd}
  listing unless the querying user is also a member of the channel.
  However, a direct @{"/WHO" link WhoCmd} or @{"/WHOIS" link WhoIsCmd} query will list your joined channels
  unless those channels are private or secret.

  @{b}See Also:@{ub} @{"/MODE" link ModeCmd}@{"Channel Mode Window" link CModeWindow}
@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Registration information
@remark ***********************************************************

@node Registration "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@prev Commands
                           _______________________
                            @{b}Product Registration@{ub}
                           ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      Grapevine V1.0 is a freely distributable program.  You can use it all
  you want at no cost, and make copies of it in accordance with the program
  License.  However, future major revisions of Grapevine will NOT be free.
  This version of Grapevine (and subsequent minor updates for bug fixes and
  minor additions) is the only version that will be publically available.

  In order to receive future versions of Grapevine, you must register.
  The registration price is $25 US.  When you register, you will be
  entitled to receive a copy of the registered Grapevine on disk when it
  becomes available.  Note that you will not necessarily receive your
  copy immediately.  The advanced features of Grapevine V2.0 are in
  development, so you will not receive a copy until it is available.  By
  registering the program now, you will be showing your support for
  continued development of Grapevine as well as your satisfaction with
  Grapevine V1.0.

  Some of the advanced features that will be available in registered
  versions of Grapevine include:
   
      · ARexx scripting, allowing complete control of Grapevine and the
        addition of your own features and commands
      · Event traps which cause execution of a script when certain messages
        are received or when other events occur
      · Netsplit trapping/handling
      · Text clipping and pasting
      · Command aliases
      · NOTIFY command to periodically check for signon/signoff of
        specified users
      · Allow user to save current state of windows (position, channels
        joined, etc.) and recreate that state when Grapevine is loaded.
      · Online context-sensitive help and gadget help.
      · Logging of messages and public discussion to disk files

  For a more complete list of planned features, refer to the @{"ToDo" link ToDo/Main} file.

  A @{"Registration Order Form" link Registration_Form/Main} has been included with the program for your
  convenience.  You can print this form out and mail it to the author.

@endnode

@remark ***********************************************************
@remark ** Support info
@remark ***********************************************************

@node Support "Grapevine Amiga Internet Relay Chat Client User Manual"
@next ""
                         ___________________________
                           @{b}Grapevine Online Support@{ub}
                         ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
      Online support for Grapevine is available in several forms, each
  described below.

  @{u}@{b}Grapevine FTP Support Site@{uu}@{ub}
  The current version of Grapevine and the DCC programs are available on
  the official Grapevine support site.
  
     site: helser56.res.iastate.edu
      dir: pub/grapevine

  In addition to Grapevine the support site contains a number of text files
  to supplement the Grapevine documentation, including IRC tutorials
  and a complete list of operational IRC servers.

  @{u}@{b}Mailing List@{uu}@{ub}
  An online mailing list was created for the discussion of Grapevine.  It
  is @{b}highly recommended that you subscribe@{ub} to the list.  You can post to
  the mailing list to report bugs, ask questions, and offer suggestions.
  The advantage of the mailing list over directly emailing the author
  is that many people can participate in the discussion and offer their
  input.  Furthermore, you will always be aware of bugs and problems
  other people have found when they are reported to the mailing list.

  To subscribe to the Grapevine mailing list, send email to

     majordomo@icecube.cryogenic.com

  In the @{b}message body@{ub}, include the line:

     subscribe grapevine

  You will be automatically subscribed to the mailing list for immediate
  participation.  To post to the list, send mail to:

     grapevine@icecube.cryogenic.com

  @{u}@{b}Author on IRC@{ub}@{uu}
  If you only have a quick question or problem, you can send a message to
  the author on IRC.  The author's IRC nickname is @{b}RedWine@{ub}, and he is
  almost always signed onto IRC (one of the advantages of having a personal
  machine on the Internet).  If you want to report bugs, or need help with
  a problem that will take some time to solve, please post to the mailing
  list instead.

@endnode

